---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
import Code from '../../components/Code.astro';
import { href } from '../../lib/site';
---

<Docs
  title="Repository layout"
  eyebrow="Documentation · Reference"
  summary="Where everything lives. The whole repo is meant to be read — there's no generated or hidden state."
>
  <p>
    The structure is deliberately flat and legible. Configuration lives under
    <code>dotfiles/</code>, the installer lives under <code>setup/</code>, and
    the marketing and docs site (the pages you're reading) lives alongside them.
  </p>

  <Code caption="ubuntu_setup/">
    ubuntu_setup/
    ├── setup/
    │   ├── bootstrap.sh        <span class="tok-comment"># the one entry point</span>
    │   ├── packages.txt        <span class="tok-comment"># apt package list — edit freely</span>
    │   ├── blocklist.txt       <span class="tok-comment"># distraction domains — edit freely</span>
    │   ├── firefox/
    │   │   └── policies.json   <span class="tok-comment"># hardened browser + uBlock policy</span>
    │   ├── lib/
    │   │   └── common.sh       <span class="tok-comment"># logging, symlink, backup helpers</span>
    │   └── steps/
    │       ├── 10-apt.sh
    │       ├── 25-herdr.sh
    │       ├── 20-mise.sh
    │       ├── 30-dotfiles.sh
    │       ├── 40-privacy.sh   <span class="tok-comment"># turn off calls home</span>
    │       ├── 45-dns.sh       <span class="tok-comment"># encrypted DNS (Quad9 DoT)</span>
    │       ├── 50-hardening.sh <span class="tok-comment"># firewall, updates, sysctl</span>
    │       ├── 60-power.sh     <span class="tok-comment"># battery + framework fixes</span>
    │       └── 70-firefox.sh   <span class="tok-comment"># browser + blocklist</span>
    ├── dotfiles/
    │   ├── bashrc              <span class="tok-comment"># → ~/.bashrc</span>
    │   ├── bash/aliases.sh     <span class="tok-comment"># sourced by bashrc</span>
    │   ├── herdr/config.toml   <span class="tok-comment"># → ~/.config/herdr/config.toml</span>
    │   └── gitconfig           <span class="tok-comment"># → ~/.gitconfig</span>
    ├── src/                    <span class="tok-comment"># this website (Astro)</span>
    └── README.md
  </Code>

  <h2 id="setup">setup/</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><code>bootstrap.sh</code> — the single entry point. It sources <code>lib/common.sh</code>, then runs each file in <code>steps/</code> in order.</li>
    <li><code>packages.txt</code> — the apt package list, one per line. Comments with <code>#</code> are ignored. Edit this before running to change what's installed.</li>
    <li><code>blocklist.txt</code> — the distraction domains, one per line. The <code>firefox</code> step compiles these into uBlock rules. See <a href={href('/docs/focus/')}>Browser &amp; focus</a>.</li>
    <li><code>firefox/policies.json</code> — the hardened Firefox enterprise policy that force-installs uBlock Origin.</li>
    <li><code>steps/</code> — numbered stages. The prefix sets the order; each file is standalone and re-runnable.</li>
    <li><code>lib/common.sh</code> — shared shell functions: <code>log</code>, <code>link_file</code> (with backup), and <code>have</code> (command detection).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="dotfiles">dotfiles/</h2>
  <p>
    Each file here maps to a target in your home directory. The naming drops the
    leading dot so the files are visible in the repo; the dotfiles step adds it
    back when it symlinks:
  </p>
  <Code>
    dotfiles/bashrc            →  ~/.bashrc
    dotfiles/herdr/config.toml →  ~/.config/herdr/config.toml
    dotfiles/gitconfig         →  ~/.gitconfig
  </Code>
  <p>
    Because they're symlinks, editing the file in the repo updates your live
    config immediately — and <code>git status</code> shows exactly what you've
    changed from the baseline.
  </p>

  <h2 id="site">src/</h2>
  <p>
    The website is a standard Astro project and is completely independent of the
    setup — you can delete it in your fork if you only want the dotfiles. It's
    included so the project can document and market itself from the same repo.
  </p>

  <p>
    Next: <a href={href('/docs/customizing/')}>Customizing</a> covers how to
    change any of this safely.
  </p>
</Docs>
